WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.660 --> 00:00:09.180
Hello, welcome, everyone.

00:00:13.580 --> 00:00:17.610
My name's Matias Duarte, and I'm
here to tell you a little bit

00:00:17.610 --> 00:00:23.580
about Material now--
right here, right now.

00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:27.940
So happy birthday, Material.

00:00:32.009 --> 00:00:33.890
It's kind of a cheat.

00:00:33.890 --> 00:00:37.550
We haven't actually
reached a full year.

00:00:37.550 --> 00:00:40.370
We're one month
shy, but it's still

00:00:40.370 --> 00:00:42.775
a pretty amazing milestone,
a pretty exciting milestone.

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:50.300
Last year at I/O, we
introduced Material Design.

00:00:50.300 --> 00:00:55.040
We wanted to make a system
for designing across platforms

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:57.030
and across screen sizes.

00:00:57.030 --> 00:01:02.700
We wanted to combine the
best of modern graphic design

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:07.820
with the real utility and
usability of surfaces.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:09.340
And most of all,
we wanted to create

00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:13.380
a system that put motion
at the heart of design

00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:16.610
and didn't slap it on
as an afterthought.

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:19.350
And, believe it or
not, when we did this,

00:01:19.350 --> 00:01:21.780
and we brought it to
you all last year,

00:01:21.780 --> 00:01:25.354
we didn't actually know
how it would be received.

00:01:25.354 --> 00:01:26.395
We were a little nervous.

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:33.640
And it turns out, we actually
got some love for it.

00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:35.140
Right on the first
day, we started

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:38.980
seeing some pretty nice quotes.

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:42.890
The tech press was able
to see and understand

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:46.270
what Material was about.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:49.220
Developers started
responding immediately

00:01:49.220 --> 00:01:52.480
with real appreciation for
what Material was about.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:57.020
And, of course, most
importantly, designers

00:01:57.020 --> 00:01:59.250
seemed to really
understand what we

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:01.540
were trying to do
with Material-- trying

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:04.990
to create a system that
would help and support them

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:07.580
in the challenges that
they have designing

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:11.070
for all the interactive
platforms that we have.

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:17.200
So, phew, like, yeah, we could
all leave the I/O keynote,

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:18.785
go to the bar, have
a drink, relax.

00:02:21.370 --> 00:02:23.010
So this made us
feel really good,

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:25.140
at least maybe, for
that first week.

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:27.760
But the real question
that we have,

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:31.470
and I'm sure a question that
a lot of you have as well,

00:02:31.470 --> 00:02:36.610
is, how useful is Material?

00:02:36.610 --> 00:02:39.230
And because we're
Google, we like numbers,

00:02:39.230 --> 00:02:43.140
so we're going to take a look at
Material Design by the numbers

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:46.350
to start off this session.

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:48.150
Let's start looking
at our guidelines,

00:02:48.150 --> 00:02:51.060
the Material Design guidelines,
what we affectionately call

00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:56.390
the 'spec.' Over the last year,
a little less than a year,

00:02:56.390 --> 00:03:01.470
it had 2.5 million
unique visitors.

00:03:01.470 --> 00:03:02.740
I think that's pretty good.

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:04.573
I mean, maybe if you're
a YouTube celebrity,

00:03:04.573 --> 00:03:07.480
or you're doing cat
videos, that's not so good.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:13.670
But for a design guideline, we
thought that was pretty good.

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:16.210
In fact, even more importantly
that that, more than half

00:03:16.210 --> 00:03:23.760
of you, in fact, over 60% of
you are returning visitors.

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:25.870
And that means Material
Design wasn't just

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:28.870
something you checked out
once, but it was actually

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:31.260
a recurring, useful reference.

00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:35.070
And we see tremendous
activity in the color section,

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:39.010
in the typography section,
in the iconography section,

00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:43.610
and, of course, in the
component section, like the FAB

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:47.670
and other specifications
like that.

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:51.100
So not just designers
seem to be getting

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:57.750
some use out of Material,
but developers as well.

00:03:57.750 --> 00:04:03.580
If we look at Polymer, which
is Google's system for bringing

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:07.320
Material components
to the web, we

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:13.840
see that developers have
looked at Polymer's paper

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:17.700
elements also 2 and
1/2 million times--

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:21.186
the specifications for how to
use Polymer paper elements.

00:04:21.186 --> 00:04:23.560
And more importantly than how
many times they've actually

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:27.100
referenced these is
how many paper elements

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:29.480
are actually integrated
into products,

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:34.000
which has been 100,000
paper elements out there

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.540
on the web, which is really
good for a framework that

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:41.490
wasn't even out of beta
until Jason announced it

00:04:41.490 --> 00:04:42.120
this morning.

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:45.950
Now, of course,
you're all wondering

00:04:45.950 --> 00:04:51.100
about Android--
Material on Android.

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:55.580
Now, it has been pretty exciting
to see Material apps come out

00:04:55.580 --> 00:04:56.870
on Android.

00:04:56.870 --> 00:04:58.890
And if we look at
them by the numbers,

00:04:58.890 --> 00:05:04.000
we see nearly a quarter
million material apps

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.710
in the Play Store, apps that
are taking advantage of Material

00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:11.370
Design by either targeting
Lollipop or using

00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:14.350
appcompat libraries.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:16.810
Now, maybe that number doesn't
seem big enough for you.

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:18.700
Your thinking, oh,
my gosh, there's

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:21.060
like a billion Android
devices out there,

00:05:21.060 --> 00:05:23.130
or how many did
gajillion Android

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:27.230
apps have been in the Play
Store over the last seven years.

00:05:27.230 --> 00:05:29.130
But if we put that
number in perspective,

00:05:29.130 --> 00:05:34.570
and we think about Lollipop
being released in October

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:40.470
of last year, and we look at
how many new apps, new Android

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:44.260
apps, entered the Play Store
since Lollipop was released,

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:49.920
we see that the materialized
apps account for more than 40%

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:51.590
of those apps.

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:54.570
More than 40% of the new
apps in the Play Store

00:05:54.570 --> 00:05:55.540
are materialized.

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:57.290
And when you think
about how many of those

00:05:57.290 --> 00:05:59.870
apps happen to be
games, that number

00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:01.020
starts looking really good.

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:05.790
That means that basically more
than one in three new apps

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:09.809
are taking advantage
of Material.

00:06:09.809 --> 00:06:11.100
Yeah, you can applaud for that.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:13.680
That's OK.

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:16.000
No, it is actually a
really exciting start.

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:24.280
But we want to make
that number even bigger.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:28.310
Design is never
done, so we're going

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:29.860
to spend a little
bit of time now

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:33.780
talking about how we can
make those numbers bigger,

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:36.330
how we can make those
numbers grow faster,

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:40.630
how we can make it easier for
all of you to bring Material

00:06:40.630 --> 00:06:42.600
into your apps and
into your designs.

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:50.230
We've been continuously updating
the Material Design guidelines

00:06:50.230 --> 00:06:51.780
to be better and
more comprehensive

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:52.980
since we launched.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:55.710
And since we launched it,
we've updated the guidelines

00:06:55.710 --> 00:06:57.580
two times already.

00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:00.340
The first time, in
November of last year,

00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:05.310
we gave you all sorts of new
sections on organizing objects,

00:07:05.310 --> 00:07:07.690
navigation drawers,
scrolling techniques,

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:11.410
as well as swipe to
refresh product icons.

00:07:11.410 --> 00:07:15.800
In April, we gave you
another update, more guidance

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:19.070
around app structured,
data tables.

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:21.450
We give you writing
guidelines for Material,

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:23.500
a whole bunch of other things.

00:07:23.500 --> 00:07:27.580
Today, we're giving you the
biggest update to the Material

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:30.542
guidelines since
we launched them--

00:07:30.542 --> 00:07:33.380
a whole bunch of new stuff.

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:37.190
So it includes refinements
to design patterns that you

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:41.260
know and love, like the FAB.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:45.420
Turns out, a lot of you
really liked using the FAB.

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:48.730
When we launched the spec, we
only provided limited guidance

00:07:48.730 --> 00:07:50.710
on how you could use
the floating action

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:53.890
button and the different
ways it could transform.

00:07:53.890 --> 00:07:57.397
But many of you thought that
the FAB could be more flexible

00:07:57.397 --> 00:07:59.480
and that you could use it
to trigger a whole bunch

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:02.620
of new things, and we agree.

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:05.960
So today, we've expanded
the number of patterns

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:08.660
at the FAB supports
and trying to give you

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:10.870
a little bit more
flexibility in how

00:08:10.870 --> 00:08:13.810
you can integrate the floating
action button into your apps.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.550
Since so many of you are
visiting the guidelines

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:24.480
for help with icons, we
decided to invest in a brand

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:27.630
new dedicated resource for that.

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.210
So today, we're
expanding the spec

00:08:30.210 --> 00:08:34.049
to include the
Material Icon Library.

00:08:34.049 --> 00:08:40.500
This site basically contains
750 icons, more than 750 icons,

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:44.520
for you to use in your projects,
in an easily organized way

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:47.660
that you can browse through and
that you can search through,

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:51.220
and that gives you one click
easy downloads for icons,

00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:53.580
for integration
into your projects.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:56.330
App developers can
just find exactly what

00:08:56.330 --> 00:08:58.590
you need in all the
screen resolutions and all

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:02.140
the densities that
you need in one place.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:04.500
More than that,
for web developers,

00:09:04.500 --> 00:09:09.920
we're actually releasing all
of the icons as a web font.

00:09:09.920 --> 00:09:14.150
Yeah, it's very cool, and
it has a super cool feature

00:09:14.150 --> 00:09:17.100
that makes it very
easy to integrate icons

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:22.250
whereby using the ligature's
features of modern type

00:09:22.250 --> 00:09:25.530
systems, you're actually
able to type the icon name

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:29.602
and have it ligature
itself into the icon.

00:09:29.602 --> 00:09:31.060
If you're a type
geek, you'll think

00:09:31.060 --> 00:09:32.430
this is the coolest thing ever.

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:42.040
We have a whole talk tomorrow
about Material Design icons--

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:46.140
Material Design Icons
Made Easy at 10:30 AM,

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:48.330
if you want to learn more
about how to use the site,

00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:53.250
how to use the font, all
the extra fun stuff there.

00:09:53.250 --> 00:09:57.240
Now, one of your biggest
requests about Material Design

00:09:57.240 --> 00:10:01.820
was help in adapting designs
and layouts to different screen

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:03.260
sizes.

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:06.140
So today, we're adding
a major new section

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:08.770
to the guidelines
specifically focused

00:10:08.770 --> 00:10:12.580
on adapting Material layouts.

00:10:12.580 --> 00:10:14.535
We're providing
detailed guidance

00:10:14.535 --> 00:10:19.910
on break points between layouts,
a scalable consistent grid,

00:10:19.910 --> 00:10:22.290
surface behaviors
and relationships

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:24.790
across those break points.

00:10:24.790 --> 00:10:28.730
So these adaptive guidelines and
examples, these new patterns,

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:31.670
are going to help you
create apps that gracefully

00:10:31.670 --> 00:10:35.560
adapt to any context.

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:38.610
We have a talk on
understanding the details

00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:40.390
of these new patterns,
also tomorrow

00:10:40.390 --> 00:10:44.490
at 9:00 AM and later at 1:30
PM, if the party tonight

00:10:44.490 --> 00:10:46.170
is a little too good for you.

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:53.690
Now, combined with these new
patterns for adaptive design,

00:10:53.690 --> 00:10:58.680
we're releasing another section
of the site-- a device metrics

00:10:58.680 --> 00:11:00.400
reference.

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:02.730
Now, this reference
is going to help

00:11:02.730 --> 00:11:04.930
you get all the
types of information

00:11:04.930 --> 00:11:08.360
you might want for designing
for arbitrary devices,

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:10.920
whether they're wearables,
whether they're phones,

00:11:10.920 --> 00:11:13.090
whether they're tablets,
whether they're laptops.

00:11:13.090 --> 00:11:15.670
You're going to be able to
get key dimensions, densities,

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:17.400
and all those other metrics.

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:20.070
But, most importantly,
this reference

00:11:20.070 --> 00:11:22.980
helps you understand for the
screen size is that you're

00:11:22.980 --> 00:11:25.950
interested in how
to plug those values

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:29.670
in to the adaptive templates.

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:31.670
This means you're going
to be able to understand

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:35.130
which template and which
pattern in these new adaptive

00:11:35.130 --> 00:11:38.300
templates you should be
using for which devices,

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:40.240
which orientation.

00:11:40.240 --> 00:11:41.890
These two resources
together are going

00:11:41.890 --> 00:11:45.770
to take all of the uncertainty
that you have right now out

00:11:45.770 --> 00:11:50.250
of creating layouts that scale
across different screen sizes

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:51.660
and orientations.

00:11:51.660 --> 00:11:55.040
And we hope it'll be really,
really useful for you.

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:05.280
Well, you guys kept asking
for it, so I hope you like it.

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:07.710
And, of course, there's
a lot more updates

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:10.270
in the guidelines themselves.

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:12.610
We have a new
section on describing

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:14.940
motion in meaningful
ways, sections

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:18.960
on launch screens, empty
states, and a ton more updates

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:21.990
and refinements.

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:24.790
Now, as Material
Design has evolved,

00:12:24.790 --> 00:12:27.090
more and more
products across Google

00:12:27.090 --> 00:12:30.300
are also implementing the
guidelines into their systems

00:12:30.300 --> 00:12:31.630
and platforms.

00:12:31.630 --> 00:12:34.740
So today, we're also
releasing new guidelines

00:12:34.740 --> 00:12:38.390
that specifically
target television, auto,

00:12:38.390 --> 00:12:42.820
and VR in the form
of Google Cardboard.

00:12:42.820 --> 00:12:46.310
We have a talk on
designing for VR tomorrow

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:50.530
at 11 AM and a talk on
Designing for Driving

00:12:50.530 --> 00:12:56.550
tomorrow at 12:30 that'll dive
deeper into these guidelines.

00:12:56.550 --> 00:13:01.590
Together, all of this really
makes it our biggest update

00:13:01.590 --> 00:13:06.230
to material Design, the
specification, the guideline,

00:13:06.230 --> 00:13:09.290
the system that
helps you design.

00:13:09.290 --> 00:13:11.120
We hope you'll like
that, and we hope

00:13:11.120 --> 00:13:12.640
you'll continue to
give us feedback,

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:16.930
so we can continue to give you
even more updates in the months

00:13:16.930 --> 00:13:17.860
and years to come.

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:23.470
We wanted to do something
a little more though.

00:13:23.470 --> 00:13:27.870
We wanted to go beyond
just guidelines, tools,

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:32.080
and references that
are perhaps static,

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:37.410
dry, authoritative,
fixed in those ways.

00:13:37.410 --> 00:13:43.410
So today, we've refreshed the
official Google Design site

00:13:43.410 --> 00:13:46.470
to be a place where our
designers can connect directly

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:49.500
with the community of
designers and developers.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:53.842
We want to have a place where
we can share why we're thinking

00:13:53.842 --> 00:13:55.550
about things the way
that we're thinking,

00:13:55.550 --> 00:13:59.390
how we go about designing,
a place where we can host

00:13:59.390 --> 00:14:04.880
practical articles, for example,
articles and videos addressing

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:07.630
common concerns for designers
and developers that are working

00:14:07.630 --> 00:14:12.430
in Material, like, "How Can I
Go Material Without Losing My

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:14.040
Brand Identity?"

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:16.730
This article's gone live
today, and we have a talk

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:20.280
also complementing it tomorrow
on Expressing Your Brand

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:23.900
Material, also at 12:30.

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:28.310
Or articles with tips
on designing easily

00:14:28.310 --> 00:14:31.680
between different platforms,
whether you're starting on iOS

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:34.580
or starting on Android
or starting on the web,

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:38.025
we want you to be comfortable
using Material everywhere.

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:46.760
And, of course, more tutorials
and, what I personally

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:51.660
enjoy the most, some
behind-the-scenes videos,

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:54.310
footage, and lots
more things like that.

00:14:54.310 --> 00:14:56.900
So I hope you'll check that
out, and I hope that will also

00:14:56.900 --> 00:15:00.120
be useful for you.

00:15:00.120 --> 00:15:05.330
Now, all these things
are great for designers

00:15:05.330 --> 00:15:07.080
when you're thinking
about what you

00:15:07.080 --> 00:15:10.550
want to express in Material.

00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:13.020
But the other thing
you kept asking us for

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:16.780
was more help in actually
implementing material.

00:15:16.780 --> 00:15:18.774
And since this is a
developer conference,

00:15:18.774 --> 00:15:20.190
you know it seems
like a good time

00:15:20.190 --> 00:15:22.035
to talk about what we've
done there as well.

00:15:24.580 --> 00:15:27.350
So, of course, we want
to start with Polymer.

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:30.180
Last year we announced Polymer,
and, as we've said today,

00:15:30.180 --> 00:15:32.670
as Jason announced
today, Polymer

00:15:32.670 --> 00:15:36.010
has gone into 1.0 out
of developer preview,

00:15:36.010 --> 00:15:37.870
out of beta today.

00:15:37.870 --> 00:15:41.310
What that means is that Polymer
is far more performant, far

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:46.100
more stable, and has a
fixed set of APIs now.

00:15:46.100 --> 00:15:48.140
And Polymer has
really been scoped

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:51.830
across all modern web
platforms, including

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:54.140
modern mobile platforms.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:55.700
So if you're designing
with Polymer,

00:15:55.700 --> 00:15:57.270
you're building
with Polymer, you

00:15:57.270 --> 00:16:00.480
have something that can
really scale to all the places

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:02.580
that the web wants to go.

00:16:02.580 --> 00:16:04.210
They tell me that
they've rewritten

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:08.300
every single line of code
in Polymer for speed,

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:09.940
and it is blazing fast.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:12.220
And what this means,
if you're using

00:16:12.220 --> 00:16:15.730
Material Design with Polymer,
is that all of those Material

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:17.940
paper elements that
you've been using so far,

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:21.010
they are now ready
for production,

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:24.890
letting you build high quality
app-like experiences anywhere

00:16:24.890 --> 00:16:26.850
on the web.

00:16:26.850 --> 00:16:30.060
In addition to that, there's
a new Polymer starter kit

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:33.840
and a catalog that is going
to allow you to learn and play

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:36.010
with all of these
new paper elements

00:16:36.010 --> 00:16:39.040
another Polymer elements
before you even get started

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:41.120
building a materialized app.

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:45.140
It includes demos, samples,
very easy browsing,

00:16:45.140 --> 00:16:47.240
and what they tell me is
a really cool shopping

00:16:47.240 --> 00:16:49.600
cart so that you can just
download Polymer paper

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:51.740
elements without having
