00:16:56.010 --> 00:17:00.696
Of course, on Android,
Material is available in L,

00:17:00.696 --> 00:17:04.339
and you will notice it is
faster and more battery

00:17:04.339 --> 00:17:08.020
efficient in the M
developer preview.

00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:10.910
But there are two
things that you're all

00:17:10.910 --> 00:17:13.990
asking for out of
Material and Android;

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:16.880
you want more
turn-key components,

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:21.460
and you want backwards
compatibility.

00:17:21.460 --> 00:17:24.310
So the Support Library
family has always

00:17:24.310 --> 00:17:27.109
been our traditional answer
to backwards compatibility.

00:17:27.109 --> 00:17:30.170
It's a plug-and-play
system that makes

00:17:30.170 --> 00:17:31.820
it possible to
implement features

00:17:31.820 --> 00:17:33.420
from the newer
versions of Android

00:17:33.420 --> 00:17:36.330
into apps deployed
on older versions.

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:38.740
And when we launched
Material last year,

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:41.500
we gave your appcompat
library, which

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:44.510
gave you some basic layout
support for Material

00:17:44.510 --> 00:17:47.600
and some basic styling.

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:50.450
Today, we're introducing
a new library

00:17:50.450 --> 00:17:55.120
in the Support Library family,
the Android design Library.

00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:58.220
And this library enables
you to take both the core

00:17:58.220 --> 00:18:01.540
elements of Material Design
to these previous versions

00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:03.880
of Android, and,
most importantly,

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:07.310
it gives you really turn-key
encapsulated implementations

00:18:07.310 --> 00:18:10.040
of all of the major
Material Design elements

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:11.970
that you've been asking for.

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:15.630
So let's look at some
of those elements.

00:18:15.630 --> 00:18:18.490
Before, even though the
FAB was a relatively simple

00:18:18.490 --> 00:18:20.700
implementation, you still
have to stitch together

00:18:20.700 --> 00:18:23.340
maybe five or six XML files.

00:18:23.340 --> 00:18:27.384
Today, you can just add a single
floating action button tag,

00:18:27.384 --> 00:18:28.050
and you're done.

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:38.040
The new library includes
an easy off-the-shelf card

00:18:38.040 --> 00:18:45.560
implementation with
shadows, side navigation,

00:18:45.560 --> 00:18:48.360
which we know is
very complicated

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:51.540
to implement with all
the details in the spec.

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:55.420
Now you can just drop in a
Navigation Drawer view and all

00:18:55.420 --> 00:18:57.470
of the details,
metrics, behaviors

00:18:57.470 --> 00:18:58.950
are taken care of for you.

00:19:03.450 --> 00:19:08.210
You Just put your Drawer items
in a menu tag, and that's it;

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:10.630
you're ready to go.

00:19:10.630 --> 00:19:12.860
Similarly, we're
making it just as easy

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:17.360
to build Material
tabs into your app.

00:19:17.360 --> 00:19:21.610
And one of my favorites is
the toolbar scrolling, also

00:19:21.610 --> 00:19:24.700
a very complex nuanced
interactive spec,

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:27.770
and, today, every aspect
of the scrolling spec

00:19:27.770 --> 00:19:32.140
is now baked into one component,
and you can just simply specify

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:35.000
which behaviors you want--
the pinning, the collapsing,

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:36.200
the scrolling offscreen.

00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:37.170
It's all there.

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:46.790
We introduced Palette last year.

00:19:46.790 --> 00:19:49.730
Palette is fantastic
for really integrating

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:51.470
your content and your apps.

00:19:51.470 --> 00:19:54.170
Today, we're giving you
an upgrade to Palette,

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:55.710
making it six times faster.

00:19:59.050 --> 00:20:02.700
And these are just some of
the highlights of the Material

00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:04.980
capabilities that you get.

